        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Museum of Practical Geology</hi></placeName>
                    <date>June 1 | 1865</date>
                    <salute>My dear Darwin</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>Your M.S reached me safely last evening—<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
<p>I could not refrain from glancing over it on the spot and I perceive I shall have to put on my sharpest spectacles &amp; best considering cap—</p>
<p>I shall not write till I have thought well on the whole subject<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>Ever Yours | T H Huxley</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Huxley refers to CD’s manuscript of the section on pangenesis for <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7951.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Variation</hi></ref> (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4837.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to T. H. Huxley, 27 May [1865]</ref> and n. 4).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">No letter from Huxley commenting on CD’s manuscript has been found, but see the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4870.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to T. H. Huxley, 12 July [1865]</ref>, for CD’s response to Huxley’s critique.</note>
        </div>        
            
